<br>
1 wizard on some raids having it has some utility.  Almost zero utility in xp groups, soloing, or even in most raids.<br>
<br>
How do we make manaburn useful again, something to strive for, without making it trivialize content?<br>
<br>
What if manaburn didn't actually take away your mana.  It just did damage relative to your current mana capacity.<br>
<br>
This would make using manaburn in an xp group very tempting -- it wouldn't cost you DPH, it would just add to it.  Bad pull, and you could splat a mob (manaburn, nuke, nuke, dead), once every 2 hours.<br>
<br>
Wizards on raids would open up with manaburn, then nuke normally on raids.  You'd have to stagger when each wizard burned.<br>
<br>
Or, what if it did damage as if you had full mana, no matter what your current mana was?  Together with draining your current mana that is.<br>
<br>
Then, you'd use manaburn on a raid when you had drained all your mana nuking.  The spell effects of manaburn (draw mana in, burn with it) sorta supports this system as well.<br>
<br>
In XP groups, you could use it, at a sacrafice of DPH.  On raids, you'd use it when you used up your mana, or at the end of the fight if you didn't run out before the end.<br>
<br>
Right now, manaburn suffers from too many counterbalancing effects.  It requires full mana to use effectively, it drains all your mana, the ratio isn't good, you can only use it on one target every minute, and any one player can only use it once per hour.<br>
<br>
The net effect is an ability that is not all that useful.<br>
